Problems found
==============

1. Inefficient “N-queries” loop  
   • A separate round-trip to the DB is executed for every id.  
   • With only one `await` inside the loop the deletes happen **sequentially**, so the run time grows linearly with the size of the `ids` array.

2. No transaction / partial-failure handling  
   • If one of the deletes throws, the ones that have already executed are **not rolled back**.  
   • The caller has no way to know which rows were actually removed.

3. Wrong/misleading return value  
   • The function returns `ids.length`, not the number of rows the database really deleted.  
   • It over-counts when `ids` contains duplicates or IDs that do not exist and under-counts when the same row is deleted concurrently by someone else.

4. Missing input validation  
   • If `ids` is not an array, or contains values of the wrong type, `db.query` may throw or the query will silently do nothing.  
   • `ids.length` will crash with “undefined has no property length” if the caller passes e.g. `null`.

5. Un-handled promise rejection  
   • Any error propagated from the DB will bubble up; if the caller does not `catch` it, Node will emit an unhandled-rejection warning or crash.

6. Potential denial-of-service / resource exhaustion  
   • A malicious caller can supply an array with hundreds of thousands of IDs. Running that many individual queries can starve the connection pool or event loop.

7. Security foot-guns when the code is later “optimized”  
   • Developers often try to concatenate the ids into a `'... WHERE id IN (...)'` string. If that change is made without keeping parameterisation, the code becomes vulnerable to SQL-injection. Designing the function properly now removes that temptation.

Fixes & improvements
====================

Below is a safe, fast rewrite that addresses the above issues.  It assumes Node + `pg`, but the approach is the same for any SQL client.

```javascript
/**
 * Delete many records in one statement.
 * Returns how many rows were really removed.
 */
async function batchDelete(ids) {
  // 1. Validate input up-front
  if (!Array.isArray(ids) || ids.length === 0) {
    throw new TypeError('ids must be a non-empty array');
  }
  if (ids.some(id => !Number.isInteger(id) || id <= 0)) {
    throw new TypeError('all ids must be positive integers');
  }

  // 2. Wrap the operation in a transaction
  const client = await db.connect();
  try {
    await client.query('BEGIN');

    // 3. Single, set-based delete.  The ANY() operator keeps it parametrised
    //    and efficient.  Cast to int[] (or uuid[] / bigint[] … as needed).
    const { rowCount } = await client.query(
      'DELETE FROM records WHERE id = ANY($1::int[]) RETURNING id',
      [ids]               // still one bind parameter – safe against injection
    );

    await client.query('COMMIT');

    // 4. Return the real number of rows affected
    return { deleted: rowCount };
  } catch (err) {
    await client.query('ROLLBACK').catch(() => {});
    throw err;  // propagate to caller
  } finally {
    client.release();
  }
}
```

What changed and why
--------------------

• **Set-based deletion** (`DELETE … WHERE id = ANY($1::int[])`)  
  – One round-trip instead of N.  
  – The `$1` placeholder keeps it parameterised; no injection risk.

• **Transaction**  
  – Guarantees that either all requested deletes happen or none happen.

• **`RETURNING` / `rowCount`**  
  – Lets us tell the caller exactly how many rows were removed.

• **Input validation**  
  – Prevents type confusion, unexpected undefined behaviour, and trivial DoS vectors.

• **Error handling**  
  – Proper try/catch/finally with rollback and connection release avoids leaked clients and unhandled rejections.

Other optional enhancements
---------------------------

• Chunk very large arrays (e.g. 10 000 + IDs) into smaller pieces to stay below PostgreSQL’s parameter / command-length limits.

• If the caller needs the list of IDs that were actually deleted, return `rows` from `RETURNING id`.

• Add rate-limiting / auth checks to ensure only authorised users can delete.

With these changes the function is faster, safer, and gives the caller reliable information about what the database really did.
